Modern Monetary Failure — Brief Point Form

Core cause
Monetary systems fail by design, not by malice.
Structural mechanics misalign value creation, value capture, and human behaviour over time.

1. Post-Issuance Proof Failure
Sound money historically required ongoing proof through scarcity, maintenance, or productivity.
Modern money demands effort only at issuance.
Once created, units persist without proving continued alignment with real constraints.
Result: claims outlive reality. Money becomes memory, then myth.

2. Liminal Gap Failure
A gap exists between action and consequence.
Inflation, leverage, and abstraction widen this gap.
Benefits are immediate; costs are delayed, externalised, or dispersed.
Human behaviour predictably favours short-term extraction.
This is a design flaw, not a moral one.

3. Cantillon Effect
Money is non-neutral at creation.
Those closest to issuance benefit first; others absorb dilution later.
Rewards proximity to power rather than productive contribution.
Inequality and rent-seeking emerge structurally, regardless of intent.

4. Gravity Effect
Capital flows toward liquidity, scale, and existing centres of power.
Slow, place-bound value is drained from rural, ecological, and peripheral systems.
Financial abstraction outcompetes local accountability.
Redistribution fails because the pull is structural.

System outcome
Speed is rewarded over patience.
Position over contribution.
Abstraction over stewardship.
Implication
Monetary repair is mechanical, not ideological.
Systems must require ongoing proof, compress time to consequence, neutralise issuance advantage, and resist gravitational concentration.
Otherwise, failure remains inevitable and repeatable.

